European inflation dropped in food
The accelerated inflation, registered in the eurozone, is primarily due to the growing price of food products.
The price rise in November has been higher than expected in the 13 eurozone countries, recording - after the 2.6 percent of the month of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Luxembourg-based Union Statistics Office.
Official forecasts were only 3 percent likely, the Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike U.S., British and Canadian issuer banks, did not cut the basic interest, as a pretext that the decline, along with the rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least about two percent.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in the trap 22: "There is to negotiate" on inflation so that it later does not have to intervene in this matter.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, registered in Germany, beat the twelve-year record; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation was shot in the eurozone as a result of galoping food and energy prices.
Grain prices increased by 88 percent and soy prices reached its highest level since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007, there was a lot more to pay for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil in the world market increased this year by 52%, reaching the black gold nearly $100 per barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, but for 2009 will already decrease to 1.9 percent.
According to analysts, the annual inflation will remain in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice in 2008.
