In many hospitals you save with disinfectants
Several thousands of infections produced first by the improper application of antibiotics have been recorded in hospitals this year.
Reigning hygiene circumstances in hospitals, bed hacination and staff overload do not favor control of infections, says the doctor-chief department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it is saved even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, a MRSA infection has been diagnosed in the traumatology department of the Janos Hospital.
In a hospitalized man after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this hospital earlier this year.
A wounded in a serious car accident was high from the hospital and the same patient had to return to the hospital shortly after the infection with MRSA and since then an important surgery has not been able to perform due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
Until December 10 this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection produced by multi-resistant agents have been registered in the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician of department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has been registered in hospitals safely, and no information is available from the rest.
About two thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methylicillin-oxacillin.
One-third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their nose without causing any disease.
Infections produced by SA (e.g. throat inflammation, amygdalite, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once antibiotics are exaggerated or improperly applied, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics become very resistant to antibiotics and quickly infect in inappropriate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or sepsicemia, first of all, patients with transitional or chronic immunodeficiency, patients with weakening body, elderly or low-weight people.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the Yanos Hospital there is nothing special in the MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
Infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - Tibor Nyulasi said - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
“These patients are isolated, nursing staff care for them in rubber and mask gloves and there are suitable antibiotics for their treatment,” Tibor Nyulasi said.
Hospitalized patients are previously examined to verify the presence of MRSA in your body, but even so it cannot avoid infection in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA hospital infections in most cases, however, current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of training and contamination with multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and elderly households, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate nurses carrying MRSA in their body.
In Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological samples are not fashionable.
This is also because the National Health Box does not finance these medical exams.
Thus, most cases come to public light when the MRSA infections already occur visible in the patient, said the doctor-chief department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes rigorous commitments for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological pictures.
Antibiotic therapy should be directed, i.e. microbiological tests should be done to prevent drug resistance from occurring, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Taking microbiological samples are even less common in the case of strolling patients or in basic assistance, Karolina Böröcz said.
Save with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through health personnel.
Therefore, they play a very important role in washing hands, wearing rubber gloves and masks, however also in this sense, considerable lack in hospitals are experienced.
MRSA is infected by drop transmission and direct contact between people, however, in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often rotated, beds are often very together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, you can also experience - added Karolina Börökz - that in less favorable economic situation hospitals you save with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and that is why there is greater probability for the infection.
In Karolina Böröcz’s opinion, where appropriate prevention measures are met, fewer such infections are recorded or pathogens can be stopped.
Government Programme Against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA contagion is a huge expense for the National Disease Insurance Fund, so it is fighting against it in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
Apparently the program is successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show decline trend in England.
The European Center for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (among these MRSAs) and the prevention of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
