$400 million more for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and Vice President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed on Friday three credit limit agreements for a total value of EUR 400 million to finance infrastructure for education, transport and the environment, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance the Hungarian budget for transport and environmental protection projects, which will be carried out from the grant of cohesion funds, of which the parties had previously signed a credit agreement for a value of EUR 100 million, the contract which has just signed for the remaining 200 million euros.
The credit contract of EUR 150 million is also intended to finance the budget of educational projects.
The EIB approved in total EUR 300 million for this Hungary target, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be made later, by expanding the credit agreement.
The parties signed a contract for €50 million for innovations, which the budget will mainly employ for the project of innovations and research at the University of Debrecen.
During the conversations also covered the theme of the construction of the 4th line of the Metro.
It was agreed that when Hungary finishes with the EU details of Metro funding, the issue will be dealt with that if necessary or not to amend the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this may take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has funded in Hungary a total of 113 projects worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest of the credits is in line with the EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charge for keeping the credit available to the debtor.
