After more than 60 years of confidentiality, Bad Arolsen’s Nazi archives, which describe the destinations of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million file documents, stored over 27 km of shelves to Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not until now accessible only for a "humanitary" purpose, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of an old victim or his righteous.
The eleven states in charge of their management – such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed in May 2006 to open them to searchers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow for research "particularly on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the fields and the state of health of forced workers," explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Red Cross Commission (ICRC).
Until recently, several states, such as Germany, opposed the opening of these nominative documents to the public, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or the mental hatching of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or detention orders established by the Gestapo had been gathered after war for a practical purpose: finding the countrymen deported or subjected to the mandatory work and eventually giving them a test of their entering, in order to open the pathway to their compensation.
Still today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees treat tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is a limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Research Center on Antisemitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
