The Mifid, which amend the Securities Market Act, entails the modernization of the financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and encouraging cooperation between the various supervisors in the European Union.
The new regulation will allow you to provide financial advice services to both specialized firms and natural or legal persons and create a new type of financial services firms (ESIS), financial advice companies (AFI), which join securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
Furthermore, it expands the number of systems for the execution of transactions on financial instruments, so that regulated secondary markets are added to multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems, which will compete with current stock exchange managers.
The Law also requires investment services companies to disclose information on the key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management forms on the market and requires them to keep a record of all their operations, to facilitate monitoring by the CNMV.
