Venus: Twin brother of the Earth.
Despite its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most similar to Earth, something that has not yet been planted. The European "Venus Express" probe discovered rays in the atmosphere and beads in the poles, the same ones that appear also in winter on Earth.
For three decades, researchers have suspected that there might be rays in Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. In Venus, the rays call on a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, Cris Russell from the University of California in Los Angeles tells the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous model of Urey-Miller’s life’s origin, rays caused life on Earth: storms may have caused reactions in the ocean that, on their part, have given origin to amino acids that are the basic components of life.
In Venus it is not so: if there was someday life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Washington Carnegie Institute.
Today, there can be no life on Venus’ surface: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times greater than on Earth and on the surface reign temperatures of 500°C, oscillating so that temperatures can be reached under zero.
“Possibly, Venus is a ‘diabolic’ twin on Earth, but it remains a twin,” Russell said.
The main goal of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question why Venus, so similar to Earth for its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
As since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus' research.
The latest results of research that will be presented in many articles of “Nature”, according to the researchers’ opinion, underline not only Venus’ unicity in the Solar System.
“This also shows that neighboring planets have more common characteristics with the Earth than we had assumed,” the ESA reports.
Despite the already known tempest winds in the North Pole, the researchers discovered in the southern polar region also a vortex formed by clouds that rotate faster.
This phenomenon reminds the wind flows in the highland atmospheric layers of the poles, according to a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the Solar System has the mass almost equal to Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers is almost as large.
This planet also known as dawn star or vespertin star orbit around the Sun nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day in Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars does not resemble Earth much, scientists leave the basis that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets, water had been accumulated that on Earth was left in the oceans, but at Venus it was discovered in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, Venus forms most of the atmosphere.
